# ChaiMetrics — Phase 1, Steps 1–3
## WSL + Docker setup guide

---

## Prerequisites (WSL side)
Docker Desktop must be running on Windows with WSL2 integration enabled.
Confirm from your WSL terminal:

```bash
docker --version          # Docker 24+
docker compose version    # v2.x
```

---

## Project layout

```
chaimterics/
├── docker-compose.yml    # Mongo + ml_engine + Ollama
├── Dockerfile.ml         # Python 3.11-slim ML container
├── requirements.txt      # All Phase 1 Python deps
├── data/                 # PUT YOUR JSON FILES HERE
│   ├── farms.json
│   └── ktda_pricing.json
├── scripts/
│   ├── verify_env.py     # Step 1 — checks everything is working
│   ├── seed_mongo.py     # Step 2 — loads JSON into MongoDB
│   └── weather_fetch.py  # Step 3 — pulls Open-Meteo data
└── models/               # joblib .pkl files land here (Steps 4-6)
```

---

## Step 1 — Build and start the stack

```bash
# From the chaimterics/ directory:
docker compose up --build -d

# Watch startup (Mongo health + Ollama model pull takes ~2-5 min first time):
docker compose logs -f

# Once stable, verify everything works:
docker compose exec ml_engine python scripts/verify_env.py
```

Expected output: all four checks green (packages, MongoDB, Ollama, Open-Meteo).

**Note on Ollama RAM:** Mistral 7B needs ~8GB RAM assigned to Docker.
In Docker Desktop → Settings → Resources, set Memory to 10GB+.
If RAM is tight during development, you can run Ollama locally in WSL instead:
```bash
curl -fsSL https://ollama.com/install.sh | sh
ollama pull mistral
# Then set OLLAMA_HOST=http://host.docker.internal:11434 in docker-compose.yml
```

---

## Step 2 — Seed MongoDB

# mongoimport the two array files as before:
docker compose exec mongo mongoimport --db chaimterics --collection farms --file /seed/farms.json --jsonArray
docker compose exec mongo mongoimport --db chaimterics --collection ktda_pricing --file /seed/ktda_pricing.json --jsonArray

# seed_mongo.py handles synthetic_metadata.json + creates all indexes:
docker compose exec ml_engine python scripts/seed_mongo.py

farms               : 240 documents
ktda_pricing        : ~180 documents
factory_metadata    : 1 document
weather_history     : 0 documents  (Step 3)
model_outputs       : 0 documents  (Steps 4-6)


## Step 3 — Fetch Open-Meteo weather data

This fetches 15 years × 12 collection centres = ~180 season-centre combinations.
Each needs 2 calendar-year API calls → ~360 HTTP requests total.
Already-fetched records are skipped on re-run (idempotent).

```bash
# Full fetch (run overnight or leave running — ~5-10 minutes):
docker compose exec ml_engine python scripts/weather_fetch.py

# Test with one centre first:
docker compose exec ml_engine python scripts/weather_fetch.py --centre "Marima"

# Dry-run to preview what will be fetched:
docker compose exec ml_engine python scripts/weather_fetch.py --dry-run
```

Expected final output:
```
Fetched:  180
Skipped (already in DB): 0
Total in weather_history: 180
Step 3 done. weather_history collection is ready for preprocessing.
```

---

## Connecting to MongoDB directly (optional)

```bash
# Mongosh REPL:
docker compose exec mongo mongosh chaimterics

# Quick document count:
docker compose exec mongo mongosh chaimterics \
  --eval "printjson({farms: db.farms.countDocuments(), pricing: db.ktda_pricing.countDocuments(), weather: db.weather_history.countDocuments()})"
```

---

## Stopping and restarting

```bash
docker compose down          # stop containers, keep volumes
docker compose down -v       # stop + wipe all data (full reset)
docker compose up -d         # restart in background
```

---

## Next: Steps 4–6 (preprocessing + model training)

Once Steps 1–3 are verified complete, the next scripts will be:

- `scripts/preprocess.py`  — sklearn pipeline (feature matrix from MongoDB)
- `scripts/train_xgboost.py` — XGBoost yield model → `models/xgb_yield.pkl`
- `scripts/train_sarima.py`  — per-farm SARIMA + pricing SARIMA → `models/sarima/`